        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We want to obtain CO(1-0) molecular gas maps and velocity maps for NGC 5548. The bandwidth of 1.875 (4956 kms^-1) GHz and spectral resolution of 5 kms^-1 (1.938 MHz, after averaging over 4 channels, as a tradeoff for sensitivity, since we don't need the full FDM spectral resolution) are sufficient for the expected line widths. Maiolino et al. (1997) detected the C0(1-0) line with FWHM of 140 kms^-1 for this source using the NRAO 12m single dish telescope, and we expect the smallest widths to be &gt; 10 kms^-1, based on 20kms^-1 lines observed in other nearby Seyfert galaxies e.g. NGC 4151 (Dumas et al., 2010). Baseband 1 is centered at a sky frequency of 113.43 GHz for CO(1-0) line observation, while the other 3 basebands are centered at sky frequencies of 111.46 GHz, 101.45 GHz, and 99.58 GHz for continuum observations to maximize the total aggregate bandwidth. 

We require an angular resolution of 0.5", which will allow us to probe structures down to 164 pc at the source, to resolve circumnuclear bars and rings. This angular resolution will also be sufficient for comparisons with star forming regions in optical-UV images obtained from space-based and ground-based telescopes. We do not require the ACA, since even in the most extended array configuration, structures up to 8" (~ 2.6 kpc) can be recovered.  

To cover the entire source, we require a mosaic (Nyquist sampled) of 7 pointings, with 7.98 minutes per pointing for a total of 55.84 minutes on source. At an integrated channel width of 10 kms^-1, this gives a mosaic sensitivity level of 1.5 mJy per beam (0.57 K at 0.5" angular resolution). Assuming spectral line widths of 10 kms^-1, and a conservative H2 mass to CO luminosity conversion factor of alpha_CO = 4.4 pc^-2(K kms^-1)^-1 for the Milky Way (Sandstrom et al. 2013), this allows molecular mass surface densities to be traced down to a level of ~ 3.8 x 10^6 solar masses per beam at 5 sigma, about 8 times the typical mass of giant molecular cloud (GMC) complexes observed in the Milky Way (~ 5 x 10^5 solar masses), in a region that can cover 10 such clouds of 50pc across (Omont 2007 and references therein). The upper range of masses for GMCs in the Milky Way is of order 10^6 solar masses, which means that such clouds can be detected at 5 sigma levels even if just 1 of them is located within the 0.5" beam. For circumnuclear regions where the conversion factor, alpha_CO, can be a factor of 5 to 10 lower (Sandstrom et al., 2013), we can trace gas masses of even lower surface densities at 5 sigma or higher. This gives us an increased 'mass sensitivity' in the circumnuclear regions - a similar amount of molecular gas mass will give us a higher CO line luminosity in the circumnuclear region. We note again that the alpha_CO = 4.4 pc^-2(K kms^-1)^-1 we adopted is conservative, and Sandstrom et al. (2013) give an average of alpha_CO = 3.1 pc^-2(K kms^-1)^-1 in a sample of 26 nearby galaxies. In the circumnuclear regions where line widths are of order 140 kms^-1, we can average spectral channels at the data reduction/analysis stage to achieve higher sensitivity levels to detect broad wings.	
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
